\c 12
\s The Son of Adam and the Sabbath
\r Mrk. 2:23-28; Luk. 6:1-5
\p
\v 1 About that time, on a Sabbath day, Jesus passed through some fields of wheat. His disciples were hungry and began to pick a few ears of wheat and eat the kernals.
\v 2 But the Pharisees saw it and said to Him, “Look! your disciples are doing what the Law forbids them to do on the Sabbath.”
\p
\v 3 Jesus replied:
\pi Have you never read what David did when he and his men were hungry?
\v 4 He went to the courtyard of God's tent where he was given the bread that had been on the table in God's presence. So he and his men ate them, even though only the priests are allowed to eat that bread.
\v 5 And haven't you ever realized from reading the Law that the priests work on the Sabbath day whenever they are on duty in the temple on a Sabbath, but their working is not counted as a sin?
\v 6 But I tell you that what God is doing through me is more important than the Temple.
\v 7 Let me remind you that God's Word stands written, “Rather than giving me so many sacrifices, I would rather you show mercy to your fellow man.”\x + \xo 12:7 \xt Hos. 6:6\x* If you understood what that means, you would not be calling people sinners who have done nothing wrong.
\v 8 And you should realize that I, as the prophesied Son of Adam, am the ruler who decides what can and can't be done on the Sabbath.
\s Jesus heals a man's hand on the Sabbath
\r Mrk. 3:1-6; Luk. 6:6-11
\p
\v 9 Going on from there, he came to their synagogue,
\v 10 where, according to the plan of those Pharisees, there was a man with a deformed arm. Wanting to find fault with Jesus, they asked him, “Does the law allow someone to cure a person on the Sabbath day?”
\p
\v 11 “Suppose you had a sheep which fell into a pit on the Sabbath day. Would you leave it there, or use all your strength to pull it out? Of course you would rescue your sheep on the Sabbath!
\v 12 Isn't it more important to help your fellow man than to help a sheep? Therefore our law does not forbid helping someone on the Sabbath.”
\p
\v 13 Then He said to the man, “Stretch out your arm.” The moment he stretched it out, it was healed and just as strong as his other hand.
\p
\v 14 But right after those Pharisees left the synagogue, they met together and discussed ways they could arrange to kill Jesus.
\p
\v 15 Aware of their plans, Jesus left that area. A lot of people followed Him, and He healed everyone who was sick among them.
\v 16 But He made it very clear that they were not to tell others about him,
\v 17 and this fulfilled what the prophet Isaiah forefold about him:
\q1
\v 18 This is my servant, the one I love and have chosen.
\q1 I am totally pleased with him
\q1 and my spirit will continually be with him.
\q1 He will proclaim how justice will be brought to all people groups of the world.
\q3
\v 19 He will not wrangle or raise His voice,
\q3 and he won't cause disturbances on the streets.
\q3
\v 20 He will not extinguish the hope of those who are weak,
\q3 and he will be gentle with those who have lost hope.
\q1 He will keep on working until his righteous cause is victorious,
\q1
\v 21 and people of all ethnic groups will center their hope upon him.
\s Jesus was insulted as Beelzebul
\p
\v 22 At that time a demoniac was brought to Him, blind and dumb; and He cured him, so that the man could both speak and see.
\v 23 The large gathering of people wwere completely amazed at Jesus and many were wondering out loud, “Can he be the prophecied Son of David?”
\p
\v 24 The Pharisees heard it and said, “This man is just using the power of Beelzebul, the king of demons, to expel demons.”
\v 25 Jesus knew what they were thinking and said to them,
\pi Any kingdom that breaks into civil war destroys itself, and any city or family that breaks into internal conflict will fall apart.
\v 26 And the same is true with Satan and his kingdom. It's crazy to think he would allow conflict in his ranks.
\v 27 And if you think I expell demon's using power from Beelzebul, then tell us what power other Pharisees are using to expel the demons. They also would say you're crazy.
\v 28 But if I am empowered by God's Spirit to expel demons, then God's kingdom has suddenly started an offensive operation your neighborhood.
\pi
\v 29 I am here as Satan's enemy who is bent on siezing his treasures. Take, for example, a thief. He is not going to be able to steal from a man who is well armed to oppose him unless he first overpowers that man and ties him up. That's how I work, and that's why I can take Satan's treasures.
\pi
\v 30 Anyone who does not join my side is on the other side opposing me. Those on my side help me in the harvest, and those on the other side interfere.
\v 31 And so I tell you that men may find forgiveness for every other sin and slander, but slandering the Holy Spirit places one on the other side where they will not be forgiven.
\v 32 Even if someone speaks out opposing me, the Son of Adam, he may still be granted forgiveness. But whoever speaks out opposing the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven for that, not now or ever.
\pi
\v 33 There is no middle ground in this. There are good trees with good fruit, and bad trees with bad fruit. If you see the fruit you know what kind of tree it is from.
\v 34 You are a fraternity of snakes! There's no way that you can teach good things when you are so full of evil! For what fills the heart is what bubbles up from the mouth.
\v 35 The things that come out of a good man's mouth are good, because that's what comes out from his heart. It's just the same with a bad man. He can't prevent showing what's in his heart.
\v 36 But I tell you that on the final judgment day, people will be held accountable for everything they have ever said, including things they said without thinking.
\v 37 Your own words will show whether you are innocent or guilty.
\p
\v 38 Then some of the teachers of the Law and some Pharisees interrupted Jesus and said, “Teacher, we want you to prove your authority by showing us a miraculous sign.”
\p
\v 39 He answered:
\pi “Your demand to see a miraculous sign shows that you are evil and unfaithful to God. The only miracle I will give to people like you is one that will remind you of the prophet Jonah.
\v 40 For just as Jonah was three days and nights in the sea-monster’s belly, so I, the Son of Adam, will remain three days and nights deep in the earth before raising again.
\pi
\v 41 On the judgment day, the people of Nineveh will stand up to accuse you people of this present time. They will remind you that they repented when Jonah preached to them, but when a greater prophet than Jonah came to you, you refused to repent.
\v 42 The queen of the south will also stand at the final judgment day to accuse you people of this present time. She will remind you that she came from such a long way away to hear the wisdom of Solomon, but when someone with greater wisdom than Solomon was right here among you, you refused to listen to him.
\pi
\v 43 Sometimes an evil spirit goes out from a person, looking for a better host to inhabit. But then that spirit wanders around, like a thirsty man in a desert, never finding a better place to take up residence.
\v 44 Then he says, “I will go back to that miserable place I left.” When he arrives, and finds the place unoccupied, swept clean, and fixed up.
\v 45 Then he goes and brings back with him seven other spirits more wicked than himself, and they come in and dwell there; and in the end the host’s condition becomes worse than it was at first. That is what is in the process of happening now with this miserably bad generation.
\p
\v 46 While Jesus was still teaching that large gathering his mother and brothers arrived and were standing outside, trying to find a way to speak to him.
\v 47 So someone let him know, “Your mother and brothers are standing out there wanting to talk to you.”
\v 48 He replied, “Let me introduce you to my mother and my brothers.”
\v 49 And pointing to His disciples He said, “These people right here are my mother and my brothers.
\v 50 For anyone who habitually does what pleases my Father in heaven is my brother, or my sister, or my mother.”
\p